DataElement.preferredDefinition: Identifies the type of genetic material used for the measurement.

The type of a material sample taken from a biological entity for testing, diagnostic, propagation, treatment or research purposes. This includes particular types of cellular molecules, cells, tissues, organs, body fluids, embryos, and body excretory substances.

ConceptualDomain.preferredDefinition: evaluations of the patient and the patient's disease.

ValueDomain.preferredName: CDISC SDTM Genetic Sample Type Terminology Type
ValueDomain.preferredDefinition: Terminology associated with the genetic sample type codelist of the Clinical Data Interchange Standards Consortium (CDISC) Standard Data Tabulation Model (SDTM)._Something distinguishable as an identifiable class based on common qualities.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A small nuclear RNA encoded by the human RN7SK gene. This oligoribonucleotide may play a role in the regulation of the enzymatic activity of RNA polymerase II.

Concepts.definition: A small nuclear RNA encoded by the human RN7SK gene. This oligoribonucleotide may play a role in the regulation of the enzymatic activity of RNA polymerase II.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Single-stranded complementary DNA synthesized from an RNA template by the action of RNA-dependent DNA polymerase. cDNA (i.e., complementary DNA, not circular DNA, not C-DNA) is used in a variety of molecular cloning experiments as well as serving as a specific hybridization probe.

Concepts.definition: Single-stranded DNA that is complementary to messenger RNA or DNA that has been synthesized from messenger RNA by reverse transcriptase.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: DNA found in blood plasma and other bodily fluids that is not associated with cells.

Concepts.definition: DNA found in blood plasma and other bodily fluids that is not associated with cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The DNA that is located in the photosynthetic, chlorophyll-containing organelle in the cells of young leaves and stems of higher plants.

Concepts.definition: The DNA that is located in the photosynthetic, chlorophyll-containing organelle in the cells of young leaves and stems of higher plants.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Neoplasm-derived DNA found in blood plasma and other bodily fluids that is not associated with cells.

Concepts.definition: Neoplasm-derived DNA found in blood plasma and other bodily fluids that is not associated with cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An RNA complex consisting of two complementary base-paired strands of RNA.

Concepts.definition: An RNA complex consisting of two complementary base-paired strands of RNA.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The DNA that is part of the normal chromosomal complement of an organism.

Concepts.definition: The DNA that is part of the normal chromosomal complement of an organism.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A small RNA involved in post-transcriptional mitochondrial RNA modification (RNA editing) in kinetoplastid protists.

Concepts.definition: A small RNA involved in post-transcriptional mitochondrial RNA modification (RNA editing) in kinetoplastid protists.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A diverse assortment of nascent, immature, unprocessed RNA transcripts synthesized from DNA templates that are found in eukaryotic nuclei before post-transcriptional modifications.

Concepts.definition: A diverse assortment of nascent, immature, unprocessed RNA transcripts synthesized from DNA templates that are found in eukaryotic nuclei before post-transcriptional modifications.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A long linear double-stranded polymer formed from nucleotides attached to a deoxyribose backbone and found in the nucleus of a cell; associated with the transmission of genetic information.

Concepts.definition: A long linear double-stranded polymer formed from nucleotides attached to a deoxyribose backbone and found in the nucleus of a cell; associated with the transmission of genetic information.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A sequence of single-stranded RNA, that is 20-25 nucleotides in length, which is transcribed from DNA but is not translated into a protein. This nucleic acid may regulate the transcription or translation of other genes.

Concepts.definition: A sequence of single-stranded RNA, that is 20-25 nucleotides in length, which is transcribed from DNA but is not translated into a protein. This nucleic acid may regulate the transcription or translation of other genes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A class of RNA molecule containing protein-coding information in its nucleotide sequence that can be translated into the amino acid sequence of a protein.

Concepts.definition: A class of RNA molecule containing protein-coding information in its nucleotide sequence that can be translated into the amino acid sequence of a protein.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A DNA/RNA chimera comprised of a single-stranded DNA molecule covalently bound to an internal guanosine of a RNA molecule.

Concepts.definition: A DNA/RNA chimera comprised of a single-stranded DNA molecule covalently bound to an internal guanosine of a RNA molecule.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The RNA portion of the msDNA molecule, which contains two stem-loop structures and varies widely in length across bacterial species.

Concepts.definition: The RNA portion of the msDNA molecule, which contains two stem-loop structures and varies widely in length across bacterial species.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Typically small, circular, intronless, and maternally inherited, mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) is the multicopy deoxyribonucleic acid genome of mitochondria, intracellular organelles responsible for vital respiratory chain and oxidative phosphorylation reactions in higher eukaryotes. Replicated and transcribed by a separate enzymatic machinery from that of nuclear DNA, mtDNA encodes only a subset of mitochondrial functions. (NCI04)

Concepts.definition: Typically small, circular, intronless, and maternally inherited, mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) is the multicopy deoxyribonucleic acid genome of mitochondria, intracellular organelles responsible for vital respiratory chain and oxidative phosphorylation reactions in higher eukaryotes. Replicated and transcribed by a separate enzymatic machinery from that of nuclear DNA, mtDNA encodes only a subset of mitochondrial functions. (NCI04)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A small cellular inclusion consisting of a ring of DNA that is not in a chromosome but is capable of autonomous replication.

Concepts.definition: A small cellular inclusion consisting of a ring of DNA that is not in a chromosome but is capable of autonomous replication.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Single-stranded RNA molecules that are expressed in animal cells and form complexes with Piwi proteins. They are involved in transcriptional gene silencing.

Concepts.definition: Single-stranded RNA molecules that are expressed in animal cells and form complexes with Piwi proteins. They are involved in transcriptional gene silencing.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A primary RNA transcript synthesized from a DNA template in eukaryotic nuclei which is post-transcriptionally modified and spliced to produce a mature mRNA.

Concepts.definition: A primary RNA transcript synthesized from a DNA template in eukaryotic nuclei which is post-transcriptionally modified and spliced to produce a mature mRNA.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The pri-miRNA is a primary transcript derived from a gene whose sole products are miRNA(s). A unique pathway involving the nuclear microprocessor complex participates in the cleavage of such transcripts, which can be substantially longer than the 65-110 nt pre-miRNA.

Concepts.definition: The pri-miRNA is a primary transcript derived from a gene whose sole products are miRNA(s). A unique pathway involving the nuclear microprocessor complex participates in the cleavage of such transcripts, which can be substantially longer than the 65-110 nt pre-miRNA.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The DNA that is normally located in the nucleus of a eukaryotic cell.

Concepts.definition: The DNA that is normally located in the nucleus of a eukaryotic cell.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The genomic sequence that encodes a ribosomal RNA molecule.

Concepts.definition: The genomic sequence that encodes a ribosomal RNA molecule.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: RNA that contains an intron sequence which has an enzyme-like catalytic activity. This intron sequence has been shown to fold up to form a complex surface that can function like an enzyme in reactions with other RNA molecules and thus synthesize new molecules even in the absence of protein. Synthetic ribozymes can be engineered to specifically cleave a target RNA sequence causing expression down regulation.

Concepts.definition: RNA that contains an intron sequence which has an enzyme-like catalytic activity. This intron sequence has been shown to fold up to form a complex surface that can function like an enzyme in reactions with other RNA molecules and thus synthesize new molecules even in the absence of protein. Synthetic ribozymes can be engineered to specifically cleave a target RNA sequence causing expression down regulation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Single-stranded long chain of nucleotides containing ribose. It is the end product of DNA transcription by the enzyme RNA polymerase. It is essential in protein synthesis.

Concepts.definition: Single-stranded long chain of nucleotides containing ribose. It is the end product of DNA transcription by the enzyme RNA polymerase. It is essential in protein synthesis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An RNA molecule that does not contain protein-coding sequence information and constitutes the majority of the cellular RNA (~80%). This nucleic acid associates with multiple proteins to form ribosomes, which are the organelles that drive mRNA-directed protein synthesis.

Concepts.definition: An RNA molecule that does not contain protein-coding sequence information and constitutes the majority of the cellular RNA (~80%). This nucleic acid associates with multiple proteins to form ribosomes, which are the organelles that drive mRNA-directed protein synthesis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Small RNA molecules that are present in the nucleolus. They associate with proteins to form small nucleolar ribonucleoprotein particles that are involved in modification of other RNAs.

Concepts.definition: Small RNA molecules that are present in the nucleolus. They associate with proteins to form small nucleolar ribonucleoprotein particles that are involved in modification of other RNAs.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Small nuclear RNA.  A class of abundant small nuclear RNAs involved in RNA processing (splicing, 3' end maturation).  These snRNAs associate with specific proteins to form the small nuclear ribonucleoprotein particles (snRNP) directly involved in RNA processing.  Seven known snRNAs have been termed U1 through U7 snRNA.

Concepts.definition: A small RNA molecule (100-300 nucleotides) located in the cell nucleus. This nucleic acid plays a role in RNA splicing, transcriptional regulation, telomere maintenance and rRNA modification.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A non-coding RNA that is part of the signal recognition particle. It is involved in the co-translational targeting of proteins to membranes

Concepts.definition: A non-coding RNA that is part of the signal recognition particle. It is involved in the co-translational targeting of proteins to membranes

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A long linear single-stranded polymer formed from nucleotides attached to a deoxyribose backbone.

Concepts.definition: A long linear single-stranded polymer formed from nucleotides attached to a deoxyribose backbone.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An RNA encoded by the bacterial ssrA gene. It is involved in the recycling of stalled ribosomes and the targeting of both defective mRNA molecules and incomplete nascent proteins for degradation.

Concepts.definition: An RNA encoded by the bacterial ssrA gene. It is involved in the recycling of stalled ribosomes and the targeting of both defective mRNA molecules and incomplete nascent proteins for degradation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A 20 to 25-nucleotide double-stranded RNA which is involved in a sequence-specific messenger RNA degradation process known as RNA interference.

Concepts.definition: A 20 to 25-nucleotide double-stranded RNA which is involved in a sequence-specific messenger RNA degradation process known as RNA interference.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A genetic element that is able to move from one genomic position to another.

Concepts.definition: A genetic element that is able to move from one genomic position to another.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A class of short adaptor RNAs that transfers a specific amino acid to a growing polypeptide chain at the ribosomal site of protein synthesis during translation. Each transfer RNA comprises a three-nucleotide sequence that is complementary to the triplet nucleotide coding sequence of an mRNA, conferring specificity to the amino acid being incorporated into the assembling protein.

Concepts.definition: A class of short adaptor RNAs that transfers a specific amino acid to a growing polypeptide chain at the ribosomal site of protein synthesis during translation. Each transfer RNA comprises a three-nucleotide sequence that is complementary to the triplet nucleotide coding sequence of an mRNA, conferring specificity to the amino acid being incorporated into the assembling protein.

ConceptualDomain.preferredDefinition: attributes of a patient's laboratory sample, including the source, condition, and fixative.
